<i>drum</i> taps,

747
00:45:07,205 --> 00:45:11,042
a book of civil war poems
he thought his finest,

748
00:45:11,209 --> 00:45:13,545
then turned largely to prose.

749
00:45:13,712 --> 00:45:18,091
His writings revolutionized
American literature.

750
00:45:20,510 --> 00:45:23,596
Phil Sheridan went out west
to take on a new enemy,

751
00:45:23,763 --> 00:45:27,058
declaring that the only
good Indian was a dead Indian.

752
00:45:27,225 --> 00:45:30,061
George Armstrong custer
went west, too,

753
00:45:30,228 --> 00:45:34,065
carrying with him his belief
in his own invincibility.

754
00:45:34,232 --> 00:45:38,528
In 1876, the sioux and Cheyenne
proved him wrong.

755
00:45:38,695 --> 00:45:41,489
George mcclellan stayed abroad
for three years

756
00:45:41,656 --> 00:45:43,992
after losing the election
to Lincoln.

757
00:45:44,159 --> 00:45:47,495
He heard no slander
about himself there, he said.

758
00:45:47,662 --> 00:45:49,497
Then he came home

759
00:45:49,664 --> 00:45:52,125
and got himself elected
governor of New Jersey.

760
00:45:52,292 --> 00:45:54,169
The conqueror of fort sumter,

761
00:45:54,335 --> 00:45:56,504
Pierre gustave
toutant Beau regard,

762
00:45:56,671 --> 00:45:58,006
promoted railroads,

763
00:45:58,173 --> 00:46:00,008
managed the Louisiana
state lottery,

764
00:46:00,175 --> 00:46:02,093
and got rich.

765
00:46:02,260 --> 00:46:04,053
Nathan bedford forrest

766
00:46:04,220 --> 00:46:07,640
promoted railroads, too,
but failed.

767
00:46:07,807 --> 00:46:11,019
In 1867, he became
the first imperial wizard

768
00:46:11,186 --> 00:46:13,021
of the ku klux klan

769
00:46:13,188 --> 00:46:19,110
but quit when the klan
grew too violent even for him.

770
00:46:19,277 --> 00:46:22,530
General Dan sickles
somehow escaped court-martial

771
00:46:22,697 --> 00:46:24,532
for his blunder
at gettysburg.

772
00:46:24,699 --> 00:46:27,243
He had the leg he lost
in the peach orchard

773
00:46:27,410 --> 00:46:29,078
mounted in a miniature casket

774
00:46:29,245 --> 00:46:32,457
and gave it to the army
medical museum in Washington,

775
00:46:32,624 --> 00:46:38,129
where he visited it regularly
for 50 years.

776
00:46:38,296 --> 00:46:40,256
John bell hood,
who had survived

777
00:46:40,423 --> 00:46:42,342
some of the fiercest fighting
of the war,

778
00:46:42,509 --> 00:46:43,927
died with his wife
and daughter

779
00:46:44,093 --> 00:46:47,680
in the New Orleans yellow fever
epidemic of 1878,

780
00:46:47,847 --> 00:46:51,351
leaving 10 orphaned children.

781
00:46:51,518 --> 00:46:53,978
George pickett never
overcame his bitterness

782
00:46:54,145 --> 00:46:56,981
over the destruction
of his division at gettysburg.

783
00:46:57,148 --> 00:46:58,983
Suffering
from severe depression,

784
00:46:59,150 --> 00:47:02,821
he turned down offers of command
from the ruler of Egypt

785
00:47:02,987 --> 00:47:04,823
and the president
of the United States

786
00:47:04,989 --> 00:47:08,660
and ended up
in the insurance business.

787
00:47:08,827 --> 00:47:11,830
Confederate general
James longstreet

788
00:47:11,996 --> 00:47:13,832
joined the republican party,

789
00:47:13,998 --> 00:47:16,334
served as Grant's
minister to Turkey,

790
00:47:16,501 --> 00:47:19,337
dared to criticize
Lee's strategy at gettysburg,

791
00:47:19,504 --> 00:47:21,172
and for all these things

792
00:47:21,339 --> 00:47:23,174
was considered
a traitor to the south

793
00:47:23,341 --> 00:47:26,970
by his former
comrades-in-arms.

794
00:47:27,136 --> 00:47:29,681
Frederick douglass

795
00:47:29,848 --> 00:47:31,528
continued to fight
as hard for civil rights

796
00:47:31,683 --> 00:47:33,518
as he had against slavery

797
00:47:33,685 --> 00:47:38,398
and became the most powerful
black politician in America.

798
00:47:38,565 --> 00:47:42,694
A young visitor once asked him
what he should do with his life.

799
00:47:42,861 --> 00:47:47,532
"Agitate!" The old man answered.
"Agitate! Agitate!"

800
00:47:49,200 --> 00:47:50,994
Julia ward howe

801
00:47:51,160 --> 00:47:53,997
helped lead the American woman's
suffrage association

802
00:47:54,163 --> 00:47:56,416
for 55 years.

803
00:47:56,583 --> 00:47:59,502
At her funeral in 1910,

804
00:47:59,669 --> 00:48:02,005
4,000 mourners
joined in singing

805
00:48:02,171 --> 00:48:05,258
<i>the battle hymn
of the Republic.</i>

806
00:48:05,425 --> 00:48:07,010
Colonel Washington roebling

807
00:48:07,176 --> 00:48:09,512
left the army corps
of engineers,

808
00:48:09,679 --> 00:48:12,223
finished his father's bridge
at Cincinnati,

809
00:48:12,390 --> 00:48:14,350
and went on to build

810
00:48:14,517 --> 00:48:18,813
the greatest suspension bridge
in the world in Brooklyn.

811
00:48:20,440 --> 00:48:22,984
"I have fought against
the people of the north

812
00:48:23,151 --> 00:48:26,362
"because I believed they were
seeking to wrest from the south

813
00:48:26,529 --> 00:48:28,573
"its dearest rights,

814
00:48:28,740 --> 00:48:30,909
"but I have never
cherished toward them

815
00:48:31,075 --> 00:48:33,036
"bitter or vindictive feelings,

816
00:48:33,202 --> 00:48:38,583
and I have never seen the day
when I did not pray for them."

817
00:48:38,750 --> 00:48:41,252
Robert e. Lee

818
00:48:41,419 --> 00:48:43,546
swore renewed allegiance
to the United States

819
00:48:43,713 --> 00:48:47,550
and by so doing persuaded
thousands of his former soldiers

820
00:48:47,717 --> 00:48:49,552
to do the same.

821
00:48:49,719 --> 00:48:52,555
He was weary, ailing,
and without work

822
00:48:52,722 --> 00:48:55,558
in the summer of 1865

823
00:48:55,725 --> 00:48:58,561
when an insurance firm
offered him $50,000

824
00:48:58,728 --> 00:49:01,564
just for the use
of his name.

825
00:49:01,731 --> 00:49:03,566
He turned it down.

826
00:49:03,733 --> 00:49:06,069
"I cannot consent
to receive pay

827
00:49:06,235 --> 00:49:08,571
for services
i do not render."

828
00:49:08,738 --> 00:49:13,076
He ended up in the noble
way you might have expected

829
00:49:13,242 --> 00:49:15,411
after you'd learned
to expect it.

830
00:49:15,578 --> 00:49:18,539
He was--didn't know what to
do with himself after the war.

831
00:49:18,706 --> 00:49:20,124
His profession was gone.

832
00:49:20,291 --> 00:49:22,293
Even his country was gone.

833
00:49:22,460 --> 00:49:25,296
And he was approached,
with a good deal of hesitation,

834
00:49:25,463 --> 00:49:27,131
by these people
from a little school

835
00:49:27,298 --> 00:49:29,968
called Washington college,

836
00:49:30,134 --> 00:49:32,929
and he accepted the presidency
of Washington college.

837
00:49:33,096 --> 00:49:37,684
He had an annual salary of
$1,500 and a house to live in,

838
00:49:37,850 --> 00:49:39,644
and he spent
the rest of his life

839
00:49:39,811 --> 00:49:43,523
at what after his death
was called Washington and Lee.

840
00:49:43,690 --> 00:49:46,067
"The greatest mistake
of my life," he said,

841
00:49:46,234 --> 00:49:49,028
"was taking
a military education."

842
00:49:49,195 --> 00:49:50,655
And whenever his students

843
00:49:50,822 --> 00:49:53,022
and those of the neighboring
Virginia military institute

844
00:49:53,074 --> 00:49:54,367
marched together,

845
00:49:54,534 --> 00:49:58,246
Lee made a point
of staying out of step.

846
00:49:59,998 --> 00:50:02,041
He never returned
to Arlington again.

847
00:50:02,208 --> 00:50:04,544
Once, on his way
to Washington,

848
00:50:04,711 --> 00:50:08,089
he glimpsed his old home
from a passing train.

849
00:50:09,507 --> 00:50:12,552
He died in 1870.

850
00:50:12,719 --> 00:50:16,556
In his last moments,
he went back to the war,

851
00:50:16,723 --> 00:50:19,559
ordering a.P. Hill
to bring up his troops,

852
00:50:19,726 --> 00:50:21,561
just as stonewall Jackson had

853
00:50:21,728 --> 00:50:23,813
on his deathbed
at chancellorsville.

854
00:50:28,735 --> 00:50:32,780
Then Lee called out,
"strike the tent."

855
00:50:42,707 --> 00:50:44,542
"For he will smile

856
00:50:44,709 --> 00:50:48,046
"and give you
with unflinching courtesy,

857
00:50:48,212 --> 00:50:51,549
"prayers, trappings, letters,
uniforms and orders,

858
00:50:51,716 --> 00:50:56,054
"photographs, kindness,
valor and advice,

859
00:50:56,220 --> 00:50:59,057
"and do it
with such grace and gentleness

860
00:50:59,223 --> 00:51:02,977
"that you will know you have
the whole of him pinned down,

861
00:51:03,144 --> 00:51:06,064
“mapped out,
easy to understand--

862
00:51:06,230 --> 00:51:08,066
"and so you have.

863
00:51:08,232 --> 00:51:10,568
"All things except the heart.

864
00:51:10,735 --> 00:51:13,488
"The heart he kept...
A secret to the end

865
00:51:13,654 --> 00:51:16,282
from all the picklocks
of biographers."

866
00:51:21,746 --> 00:51:25,458
"I feel that we are
on the Eve of a new era

867
00:51:25,625 --> 00:51:27,210
"when there is to be
a great Harmony

868
00:51:27,376 --> 00:51:30,630
"between the federal
and the confederate.

869
00:51:30,797 --> 00:51:32,548
"I cannot stay
to be a living witness

870
00:51:32,715 --> 00:51:34,717
"to the correctness
of this prophecy,

871
00:51:34,884 --> 00:51:40,515
but I feel it within me
that it is to be so."

872
00:51:41,641 --> 00:51:42,934
The qualities

873
00:51:43,101 --> 00:51:46,020
that served ulysses s. Grant
so well in war--

874
00:51:46,187 --> 00:51:50,024
stubbornness, independence,
aversion to politics--

875
00:51:50,191 --> 00:51:52,610
deserted him in peacetime.

876
00:51:52,777 --> 00:51:54,195
He entered the white house

877
00:51:54,362 --> 00:51:56,781
pledged to peace, honesty,
and civil rights,

878
00:51:56,948 --> 00:52:00,785
but corruption tainted
his two terms.

879
00:52:00,952 --> 00:52:04,038
After the presidency,
he settled in Manhattan,

880
00:52:04,205 --> 00:52:08,543
where he lent his name
to a wall street brokerage firm.

881
00:52:08,709 --> 00:52:10,545
Another partner in the firm

882
00:52:10,711 --> 00:52:13,548
stole millions
from the shareholders in 1884

883
00:52:13,714 --> 00:52:16,050
and bankrupted
the Grant family.

884
00:52:16,217 --> 00:52:20,805
Once again,
U.S. Grant was penniless.

885
00:52:20,972 --> 00:52:25,059
At almost the same moment,
he was found to be suffering

886
00:52:25,226 --> 00:52:28,479
from inoperable cancer
of the throat.

887
00:52:28,646 --> 00:52:32,066
Determined to provide
for his family before he died,

888
00:52:32,233 --> 00:52:35,486
he set to work
writing his memoirs.

889
00:52:35,653 --> 00:52:38,614
In the summer of 1885,
he moved to a cottage

890
00:52:38,781 --> 00:52:42,118
at mount McGregor
in the adirondacks.

891
00:52:42,285 --> 00:52:44,662
Unable now to eat or speak,

892
00:52:44,829 --> 00:52:48,166
he sat on the front porch
in the afternoons,

893
00:52:48,332 --> 00:52:50,501
laboring over his manuscript.

894
00:52:50,668 --> 00:52:54,005
He finished it on July 16

895
00:52:54,172 --> 00:52:56,382
and died one week later.

896
00:52:59,177 --> 00:53:03,014
Grant's memoirs sold
half a million copies

897
00:53:03,181 --> 00:53:05,892
and restored
his family's fortune.

898
00:53:18,696 --> 00:53:22,533
In 1913, the government held
a 50th anniversary reunion

899
00:53:22,700 --> 00:53:24,535
at gettysburg.

900
00:53:24,702 --> 00:53:27,413
It lasted three days.

901
00:53:27,580 --> 00:53:29,040
Thousands of survivors

902
00:53:29,207 --> 00:53:31,042
bivouacked
on the old battlefield,

903
00:53:31,209 --> 00:53:34,587
swapping stories,
looking up old comrades.

904
00:53:40,134 --> 00:53:42,011
The climax was to be

905
00:53:42,178 --> 00:53:44,513
a re-enactment
of pickett's charge.

906
00:53:44,680 --> 00:53:47,058
As the rebel yell rang out

907
00:53:47,225 --> 00:53:49,060
and the old confederates
started forward again

908
00:53:49,227 --> 00:53:50,770
across the fields,

909
00:53:50,937 --> 00:53:53,981
a moan, "a gigantic gasp
of unbelief,"

910
00:53:54,148 --> 00:53:57,526
rose from the union men
on cemetery Ridge.

911
00:53:57,693 --> 00:54:00,029
"It was then,"
one onlooker said,

912
00:54:00,196 --> 00:54:03,032
"that the Yankees, unable
to restrain themselves longer,

913
00:54:03,199 --> 00:54:05,534
"burst from
behind the stone wall

914
00:54:05,701 --> 00:54:08,788
"and flung themselves
upon their former enemies,

915
00:54:08,955 --> 00:54:13,042
"not in mortal combat,
but embracing them

916
00:54:13,209 --> 00:54:15,920
in brotherly love
and affection."

917
00:54:20,716 --> 00:54:22,551
"Pageant has passed.

918
00:54:22,718 --> 00:54:25,554
"The day is over,
but we linger,

919
00:54:25,721 --> 00:54:29,558
"loath to think we shall
see them no more together--

920
00:54:29,725 --> 00:54:34,563
these men, these horses,
these colors afield."

921
00:54:34,730 --> 00:54:37,066
Joshua Lawrence Chamberlain.

922
00:54:37,233 --> 00:54:40,069
Joshua Lawrence Chamberlain

923
00:54:40,236 --> 00:54:41,988
was at the gettysburg reunion,

924
00:54:42,154 --> 00:54:46,492
still imposing at 83,
despite almost constant pain

925
00:54:46,659 --> 00:54:49,495
from the unhealed
internal damage done him

926
00:54:49,662 --> 00:54:52,790
by a confederate minie ball
at Petersburg.

927
00:54:52,957 --> 00:54:57,503
The reunion was, he said,
a transcendental experience,

928
00:54:57,670 --> 00:55:01,299
"a radiant fellowship
of the fallen."

929
00:55:01,465 --> 00:55:03,009
He had received
the medal of honor

930
00:55:03,175 --> 00:55:06,012
for his courage
at little round top,

931
00:55:06,178 --> 00:55:08,639
served four terms
as governor of Maine,

932
00:55:08,806 --> 00:55:11,517
then became president
of bowdoin college,

933
00:55:11,684 --> 00:55:14,478
where he managed to teach
every subject in the curriculum

934
00:55:14,645 --> 00:55:17,106
except mathematics.

935
00:55:17,273 --> 00:55:22,069
He died
of his ancient wound in 1914.

936
00:55:24,530 --> 00:55:26,407
The war was over.

937
00:55:38,210 --> 00:55:41,172
Who won the war?

938
00:55:41,339 --> 00:55:43,841
The union army
obviously won the war

939
00:55:44,008 --> 00:55:47,011
in the sense that they were
the army left standing

940
00:55:47,178 --> 00:55:48,012
and holding their weapons

941
00:55:48,179 --> 00:55:51,015
when it was all over.

942
00:55:51,182 --> 00:55:54,518
So the soldiers who fought
in the union army,

943
00:55:54,685 --> 00:55:56,520
the generals who directed it,

944
00:55:56,687 --> 00:55:59,523
the president
who led the country during it

945
00:55:59,690 --> 00:56:02,026
won the war.

946
00:56:02,193 --> 00:56:06,030
If we're not talking
just about the series of battles

947
00:56:06,197 --> 00:56:09,158
that finished up with
the surrender at appomattox,

948
00:56:09,325 --> 00:56:12,536
but talking instead
about the struggle

949
00:56:12,703 --> 00:56:17,041
to make something higher
and better out of the country,

950
00:56:17,208 --> 00:56:19,543
then the question
gets more complicated.

951
00:56:19,710 --> 00:56:23,547
The slaves won the war,
and they lost the war

952
00:56:23,714 --> 00:56:28,969
because they won freedom,
that is, the removal of slavery,

953
00:56:29,136 --> 00:56:34,141
but they did not win freedom
as they understood freedom.

954
00:56:34,308 --> 00:56:37,228
I suppose that slavery

955
00:56:37,395 --> 00:56:43,901
is merely the--the horrible
statutory expression

956
00:56:44,068 --> 00:56:50,491
of a deeper--of a deeper rift
between people based on race,

957
00:56:50,658 --> 00:56:58,499
and that is what
we struggle still to--to heal.

958
00:56:58,666 --> 00:57:03,003
And, I think the--the
significance of Lincoln's life

959
00:57:03,170 --> 00:57:04,505
and his victory

960
00:57:04,672 --> 00:57:07,508
was that--that
we will never again

961
00:57:07,675 --> 00:57:10,511
enshrine these concepts
into law,

962
00:57:10,678 --> 00:57:15,015
but now let's see
what we can do to erase them

963
00:57:15,182 --> 00:57:18,936
from the hearts
and minds of--of people.

964
00:57:19,103 --> 00:57:20,479
The civil war

965
00:57:20,646 --> 00:57:23,524
is not only the central event
of American history,

966
00:57:23,691 --> 00:57:27,361
but it's a central event in
large ways for the world itself.

967
00:57:27,528 --> 00:57:30,030
If we believe, today, in the
20th century, as surely we must,

968
00:57:30,197 --> 00:57:32,658
that popular government
is the way to go,

969
00:57:32,825 --> 00:57:33,993
it is the way

970
00:57:34,160 --> 00:57:35,953
for the emancipation
of the human spirit,

971
00:57:36,120 --> 00:57:38,330
then the civil war
established the fact

972
00:57:38,497 --> 00:57:40,749
that a popular government
could survive,

973
00:57:40,916 --> 00:57:43,419
that it could overcome
an internal secession movement

974
00:57:43,586 --> 00:57:44,962
that could destroy it.

975
00:57:45,129 --> 00:57:47,756
So the war
becomes--in essence, it becomes

976
00:57:47,923 --> 00:57:49,800
a testament
for the liberation

977
00:57:49,967 --> 00:57:52,511
of the human spirit
for all time.

978
00:57:58,142 --> 00:58:00,478
Four million Americans
had been freed

979
00:58:00,644 --> 00:58:02,480
after four years of agony,

980
00:58:02,646 --> 00:58:05,483
but the meaning of freedom
in American life

981
00:58:05,649 --> 00:58:08,861
remained un resolved.

982
00:58:09,028 --> 00:58:11,655
"Emancipated slaves
own nothing,"

983
00:58:11,822 --> 00:58:13,657
one Tennessee planter wrote,

984
00:58:13,824 --> 00:58:17,870
"because nothing but freedom
has been given them."

985
00:58:18,037 --> 00:58:20,498
Thousands of blacks
wandered Southern roads

986
00:58:20,664 --> 00:58:25,169
searching for relatives
or looking for work or food.

987
00:58:25,336 --> 00:58:27,671
Thousands more stayed
on their plantations

988
00:58:27,838 --> 00:58:31,675
as hired hands
or sharecroppers.

989
00:58:31,842 --> 00:58:33,344
The 13th amendment

990
00:58:33,511 --> 00:58:36,347
was followed
by a 14th and a 15th,

991
00:58:36,514 --> 00:58:37,848
promising full citizenship

992
00:58:38,015 --> 00:58:40,851
and due process
for all American men,

993
00:58:41,018 --> 00:58:42,269
white and black.

994
00:58:42,436 --> 00:58:45,022
But the promises
were soon overlooked

995
00:58:45,189 --> 00:58:48,025
in the scramble
for a new prosperity,

996
00:58:48,192 --> 00:58:50,694
and white supremacy
was brutally reimposed

