00:58:50,861 --> 00:58:53,072
throughout
the old confederacy.

998
00:58:53,239 --> 00:58:56,700
The white south
won that war of attrition.

999
00:58:56,867 --> 00:58:58,702
It would take another century

1000
00:58:58,869 --> 00:59:01,205
before blacks
gained back the ground

1001
00:59:01,372 --> 00:59:05,084
for which so many
had given their lives.

1002
00:59:08,879 --> 00:59:12,716
I think what we need
to remember most of all

1003
00:59:12,883 --> 00:59:18,222
is that the civil war
is not over

1004
00:59:18,389 --> 00:59:23,227
until we, today, have done
our part in fighting it,

1005
00:59:23,394 --> 00:59:26,230
as well as understanding
what happened

1006
00:59:26,397 --> 00:59:29,316
when the civil war generation
fought it.

1007
00:59:29,483 --> 00:59:33,237
William faulkner, said once

1008
00:59:33,404 --> 00:59:39,743
that history is not "was,"
it's "is,"

1009
00:59:39,910 --> 00:59:43,664
and what we need to remember
about the civil war

1010
00:59:43,831 --> 00:59:46,166
is that the civil war

1011
00:59:46,333 --> 00:59:49,670
is in the present
as well as in the past.

1012
00:59:49,837 --> 00:59:52,172
The generation
that fought the war,

1013
00:59:52,339 --> 00:59:55,342
the generation that argued
over the definition of the war,

1014
00:59:55,509 --> 00:59:58,804
the generation that had
to pay the price in blood,

1015
00:59:58,971 --> 01:00:01,515
that had to pay the price
in blasted hopes

1016
01:00:01,682 --> 01:00:03,684
and a lost future,

1017
01:00:03,851 --> 01:00:09,648
also established a standard
that will not mean anything

1018
01:00:09,815 --> 01:00:11,984
until we have finished
the work.

1019
01:00:12,151 --> 01:00:15,195
You can say there's
no such thing as slavery anymore

1020
01:00:15,362 --> 01:00:16,864
we're all citizens.

1021
01:00:17,031 --> 01:00:21,201
But if we're all citizens,
then we have a task to do

1022
01:00:21,368 --> 01:00:24,121
to make sure that that, too,
is not a joke.

1023
01:00:24,288 --> 01:00:29,376
If some citizens live in houses
and others live on the street,

1024
01:00:29,543 --> 01:00:32,212
the civil war
is still going on.

1025
01:00:32,379 --> 01:00:34,715
It's still to be fought,

1026
01:00:34,882 --> 01:00:37,092
and regrettably,
it can still be lost.

1027
01:00:57,821 --> 01:01:02,660
<i>Gettysburg's guns are
still, and the dead sleep on.</i>

1028
01:01:02,826 --> 01:01:06,163
<i>America's most famous
battleground is a camp again</i>

1029
01:01:06,330 --> 01:01:08,207
<i>with a road dividing
the blue and gray.</i>

1030
01:01:08,374 --> 01:01:10,417
<i>There is no other
dividing line now</i>

1031
01:01:10,584 --> 01:01:13,837
<i>as 2,500 veterans gather
from north and south</i>

1032
01:01:14,004 --> 01:01:18,425
<i>to mark the 75th anniversary
of America's armageddon.</i>

1033
01:01:18,592 --> 01:01:19,677
<i>Hello.</i>

1034
01:01:19,843 --> 01:01:21,178
<i>Hello.
How are you?</i>

1035
01:01:21,345 --> 01:01:23,681
<i>Glad to see you.</i>

1036
01:01:23,847 --> 01:01:26,183
<i>Ha ha ha!
You're all right.</i>

1037
01:01:26,350 --> 01:01:28,686
<i>Woo! Woo!
Woo!</i>

1038
01:01:28,852 --> 01:01:30,688
<i>Woo! Woo!
Woo!</i>

1039
01:01:30,854 --> 01:01:32,189
<i>Ha ha ha!</i>

1040
01:01:32,356 --> 01:01:33,440
<i>That's
the rebel yell.</i>

1041
01:01:33,607 --> 01:01:35,901
Woo! Woo! Woo!

1042
01:01:36,068 --> 01:01:38,696
We think that we are

1043
01:01:38,862 --> 01:01:41,865
a wholly superior people.

1044
01:01:42,032 --> 01:01:44,660
If we'd been anything like
as superior as we think we are,

1045
01:01:44,827 --> 01:01:46,870
we would not
have fought that war,

1046
01:01:47,037 --> 01:01:48,455
but since we did fight it,

1047
01:01:48,622 --> 01:01:52,167
we have to make it
the greatest war of all times

1048
01:01:52,334 --> 01:01:55,170
and our generals were the
greatest generals of all time.

1049
01:01:55,337 --> 01:01:57,548
It's very American
to do that.

1050
01:02:34,376 --> 01:02:37,212
In time, even death itself
might be abolished.

1051
01:02:37,379 --> 01:02:40,132
Sergeant Barry Benson,
a south Carolina veteran

1052
01:02:40,299 --> 01:02:42,634
from mcgowen's brigade,
wilcox's division,

1053
01:02:42,801 --> 01:02:45,637
a.P. Hill's corp,
army of northern Virginia,

1054
01:02:45,804 --> 01:02:47,639
he had enlisted
three months before sumter,

1055
01:02:47,806 --> 01:02:50,684
at age 18,
and served through appomattox--

1056
01:02:50,851 --> 01:02:54,188
saw it so when he got around
to composing the reminiscences

1057
01:02:54,354 --> 01:02:56,523
he hoped would
"go down amongst my descendants

1058
01:02:56,690 --> 01:02:59,777
for a long time."

1059
01:02:59,943 --> 01:03:01,820
Reliving the war in words,

1060
01:03:01,987 --> 01:03:04,907
he began to wish
he could relive it in fact.

1061
01:03:05,073 --> 01:03:08,827
And he came to believe
that he and his fellow soldiers,

1062
01:03:08,994 --> 01:03:10,329
gray and blue,

1063
01:03:10,496 --> 01:03:13,457
might one day
be able to do just that,

1064
01:03:13,624 --> 01:03:17,544
if not here on earth,
then afterwards in Valhalla.

1065
01:03:17,711 --> 01:03:21,673
"Who knows?" He asked, as his
narrative drew toward its close,

1066
01:03:21,840 --> 01:03:24,676
"but it may be given to us,
after this life,

1067
01:03:24,843 --> 01:03:26,512
"to meet again
in the old quarters,

1068
01:03:26,678 --> 01:03:28,180
"to play chess and draughts,

1069
01:03:28,347 --> 01:03:31,308
"to get up soon to answer
the morning roll call,

1070
01:03:31,475 --> 01:03:35,479
"to fall in at the tap of the
